  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Edict Refusing the Retirement Request of Park Hyun-gyui, Vice Director of the Privy Council
  author: Lee Gyu-bo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    ... A minister reaching seventy may seek retirement—such is the ancient custom. Yet when a ruler depends upon but one or two counselors to govern, how rare and precious is the worthy statesman. To grant you leave would be like clipping one's own wings.

    You have served from the age of distant predecessors until now, and your path has been upright, your conduct steadfast. Your tastes align with no mere convention. Your learning of the classics runs deep, your wisdom broad—all your arguments rest upon solid ground. Through many ranks of high office you have risen, and in your tenure as censor, whenever righteousness called for action, you stepped forward without hesitation, eyes blazing with courage. When matters demanded utterance, you spoke with utmost candor, bowing to none.

    This is why we first appointed you to the crucial office of the Privy Council, intending soon to elevate you to the highest seat of state. The counsel and wisdom you have shown us are manifold and profound. Yet scarcely have you served in this inner chamber for more than a few years—why then do you suddenly cling to thoughts of self-preservation and feign grave illness?

    Moreover, in these times when northern barbarians show no restraint and the realm faces mounting troubles, this is when scholar-officials must worry for the nation's fate—not when ministers seek their ease. Wait for days of great peace, and then pursue your rest.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Park Hyun-gyui (박현규) was a high official of Goryeo who requested retirement at an advanced age, which King Seonjong refused through this royal edict.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'northern barbarians' (호羯) refer to Jurchen invasions threatening Goryeo's northern borders during this period.
  - key: ''
    value: The phrase about 'clipping one's own wings' (剪其羽翮) is a metaphor for diminishing one's own strength through the loss of capable ministers.
